President Vladimir Putin of Russia has signed a law on administrative liability for violation of the time and order of payment of goods (work, services) in procurement for public and municipal needs.
The Act is intended to address the very serious problem of the failure of contracting authorities to comply with their obligations in the conduct of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, a situation where entrepreneurs could not obtain payment under public and municipal contracts already carried out was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia commissioned the Office of the Attorney-General to take special control of the problem.
Because businessmen themselves were unable to cope with bad faith contractors who had not been supported by the financing of contracts, they tried to avoid the obligation to pay and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payments under public orders, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office has submitted 9.7 thousand submissions, resulting in disciplinary proceedings involving 4,5 thousand officials, 75 files for the administration, 533, and 46 of them have been prosecuted.
As a result, more than 66 billion roubles were owed to entrepreneurs.
However, these huge amounts have not been recovered as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
Many, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs have led to more modest amounts of debt.
That's a typical case.
The small company leader won a several million roubles social services competition.
The person invested all his working capital, fully complied with the obligations but did not receive the money in due time.
The result is an increasing financial commie from salary debts, taxes, credits that would lead to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek assistance from the prosecution.
The problem has now been maximized in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of public and municipal debt identified by prosecutors of entities in the Russian Federation was about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt levels continue to be critical, the Office of the Public Prosecutor is operating under manual anti-crisis management.
The Attorney-General personally conducts visits with representatives of the local authorities, during which all violations and measures discovered by prosecutors are dealt with in a substantive manner.
Such operational meetings were already held in Yaroslavla and Yekaterinburg this year.
The Federal Act No. 189-FZ, on the introduction of amendments to the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation, which was signed by the President of the Russian Federation last week, will be able to improve the payment of payment discipline of public contracting authorities in a manner that would enable them to implement Federal Act No. 189-FZ on the introduction of amendments to the Code on Administrative Offences to establish the administrative responsibility of the contracting authority for the breach of the time and payment of goods (work, services) in the conduct of procurement for the provision of public and municipal needs.
The draft law was drafted by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Office of the Prosecutor.
The new law will complement the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation, which provides for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 rubles for violation by the contracting authority of the time and order of payment of goods, works and services in public and municipal procurement.
If an official has already been punished by administrative authorities for a similar offence, he or she shall be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of entities of the Russian Federation have already been mandated to ensure the implementation of these legislative novels in practice.
