Even though she had promised anonymity, some staff members did not trust the process.
“He was never consistent and objective,” said Errett, manager of a 75-person company in San Francisco, Madison Reed, responsible for electronic hair-care trade.
She therefore turned to others for help.
There is now a new type of start-ups in the field of staff that help companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure the involvement of staff, they allow companies to express themselves, to apply for specific commands and demographic groups, to offer anonymousness and hotlines for complaints to staff, and in some cases to allow informers to pass the top management and direct direct contact.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Burnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup from Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used to measure staff involvement.
Errett explained that she had reached a greater understanding of what her staff thought and felt in terms of three years' use of Glint.
In addition to express interviews and questionnaires of specific commands, the product offers a company's heat map and shows in visual form, which units have more complaints and which managers have low ratings, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are less aware of the need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become the next Uber, who was involved in the scandal when a former staff member posted a post on a blog that described the aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups such as Glint, this is a desire to control the situation, an opportunity for profitable business.
According to the Internet portal “Let’s talk about pay”, dedicated to financial technologies, the global management, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Convercent launch from Denver, Colorado, to help companies prevent and detect bad behaviour, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year in the backdrop of Uber reputation.
Overcent has almost 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send individual staff interviews, collect confidential real-time responses, and browse the heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go straight to the office.
“The court of public opinion has taken over the power of the inspectors”, said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it is found that the company does not treat staff properly or behaves unethically, even if the inspector does not intervene, the company may suffer costly consequences from boycotts by clients, staff drains and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants where more than 25,000 employees work in 500 facilities, has been using theovercent for over a year to make sure that staff are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer a simple way to contact the company's main office.
Earlier, if the staff member wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or e-mail at the head office, file a formal complaint and hope that they would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, head of the Ruby Tuesday legal office, who said that there was no normal way to monitor staff complaints.
Now, when the company is using the Convercent service, the problems previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, disorder and unfair pay – can be quickly discovered and taken care of.
“I can draw closer to a comprehensive, comprehensive understanding of the situation of staff,” said Vitrano, who manages the risk management team of the Ruby Tuesday network.
“And we protect our shareholders from legal proceedings against staff”.
According to Quinland, companies began to deal more seriously with the ethics, values and involvement of staff in 2002, after Arthur Andersen, an accountant, suffered a collapse due to ethical violations resulting from Dela Enron.
But only when “social networks have received massive distribution” have companies realized that they will not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution on the network.
“Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy”, he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, taking a regular fee from companies for their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, resulting in the company's total capital of $60 million.
These investments are unlikely to be surprising if they take into account the interrelated nature of companies, cultures and venture capital.
Growing research shows that today's staff expect more from their jobs than before.
In highly competitive markets, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just a minimum.
Staff want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to the company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in companies, they feel that they are heard, and that the work they are doing results, they are trying more to make such a company a success”, says Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where Convercent and Glint are being used.
Investors receive income when companies from their portfolio are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase the dedication and involvement of staff, it is not surprising that they find support.
It is important, as culture professionals say, that data on employee involvement are available.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
Indeed, if the company requests feedback, it may give the impression that there are changes.
And if change doesn't happen fast enough, or if it doesn't come up at all, frustration may develop, and staff will lose interest.
“If you are going to ask for 4,000 suggestions, you should be ready to hold 4,000 interviews”, said Russell Rat, President of Management Consulting Kotter International, who had to see companies making a mistake, relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will say, "Have you really heard me?
You don't care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, who is now conducting monthly staff interviews, is able to take action on the same day as someone reporting the problem with Glint.
And, after feedback from staff members, dissatisfied with decision-making and communication quality, it was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is getting new knowledge of its staff and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it to retain staff more effectively in an industry known for its high turnover.
“If you do not try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people”, said Vitrano.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
