Red meat, dairy products and chocolates can help to facilitate the HPC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your food tract.
But recent studies suggest otherwise: diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help to alleviate the symptoms of those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects some 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in Britain, leads to the size and swelling of the abdomen, chronic or blood vessels, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually to relieve the symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at Washington University found that the primary amino acid protein triptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, a leading researcher, explained that the immune cells in the intestines ensure that harmful microbes that come with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much inflammation, it may lead to inflammation of the intestine.
Experts have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs triptophan -- one of the building blocks of protein -- to start the formation of these cells.
Professor Kolonna said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuterium - which is part of the normal microbiom of the intestine and the development of cell populations that increase tolerance.
The more Triptophane was contained in the feeding of mice, the more they had these immune cells.”
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuter and a rich triptophan diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation of the environment in the intestine.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganzas, who studied the variety of immune cell tolerances, found that one group of tested mice had these cells, and another group, which belonged to the same line, but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the microbiomes of the mouse’s intestines, which are communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi, which usually live in the stomach and intestine tract.
The DNA of the mouse intestine cells was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found to be present in mice with immune cells but not in mice without them.
The mice that were grown in a sterile environment without a good microbiome and which did not develop this kind of immune cell received L. reuterium, and the immune cells appeared to them.
In order to understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuterium in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of liquid - without bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells that are selected from mice.
Immun cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it was a by-product of triptophan processing, known as indole-3-molic acid.
