The White House requisition cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided by the Time magazine, the White House decision last month to send a Marine Infantry helicopter to the South Lawn at an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, became the central element of the event in the White House on 17 July, which demonstrated the American construction programmes.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and the White House senior officials reviewed technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was launched near a boat from the state of Man, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truckloader from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Infantry Squadron (HMX-1), the Department responsible for helicopter management ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of “unusual” activities.
“I just wanted you to know that you know, because this is an unusually wide coverage of the press event”, said Commander HMX-1 in an electronic letter to his superior, the first Deputy Chief of Aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the gas station was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the time limits for work.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, while the unit security officers remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by Time that the second crew had been required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 has specified whether it is contrary to this decision.
“We asked, among other things, if this was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told not to,” the commander wrote.
“You seem to have nowhere to go”, replied the Deputy Chief.
The White House was declared an official event in America, and Hatcha's law did not apply to it.
But even official activities have political notes.
In the course of the event, the President made efforts to advance the health reform of the former Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government decisions.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is unlikely to be new.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask them alone in the interest of photoopportunity.
Trump had already been the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane took a rearward course during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account collapsed with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is excited about the show “Made in America”, which presented products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” said White House Spokesperson Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and the South Lawn to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House with accuracy up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight carried out for the Americas event was counted as a required training flight per month.
The unit helicopters also flew 11 additional hours on that day as part of the “non-resident support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
The representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in the demonstration of the helicopter in the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent in the event.
However, according to the Ministry of Defence's hourly rates for 2017, the Ministry of Defence's reimbursement rate for VH-3D amounts to $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records indicate that the airtime of the aircraft was 30 minutes on each side of its airfield based on the Quantico Marine Infantry Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using the helicopter is far below that rate.
“It is completely wrong to calculate the cost for taxpayers based on an approximate rate of reimbursement”, said Walters.
“These sample rates include personal composition, services and many other irreversible costs, which are included in annual allocations”.
According to a study conducted by the RAND Corporation in 2015, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do indeed take into account the cost of fuel, services and costs indicated in the contract.
At that time, former White House Press Secretary Sean Spiser spoke in defence of the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to show this week the things that have been done in America”, said Spiser.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we're all proud of this helicopter and other military technology that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
It is therefore, of course, absolutely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he sat precisely in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
